content.text: Cleaning Data
When preparing for machine learning, it is always important to:
content.html: When preparing for machine learning, it is always important to:

content.text: Remove Data
A smart way to remove unnecessary data, it to extract only the data you need .
content.html: A smart way to remove unnecessary data, it to extract only the data you need.

content.text: This can be done by iterating (looping over) your data with a map function .
content.html: This can be done by iterating (looping over) your data with a map function.

content.text: The function below takes an object and returns only x and y from the object's Horsepower and Miles_per_Gallon properties:
content.html: The function below takes an object and returns only x and y from the object's Horsepower and Miles_per_Gallon properties:

content.code_html:
function extractData(obj) {
  return {x:obj.Horsepower, y:obj.Miles_per_Gallon};
}

content.text: Remove Errors
Most datasets contain some type of errors.
content.html: Most datasets contain some type of errors.

content.text: A smart way to remove errors is to use a filter function to filter out the errors.
content.html: A smart way to remove errors is to use a filter function to filter out the errors.

content.text: The code below returns false if on of the properties (x or y) contains a null value:
content.html: The code below returns false if on of the properties (x or y) contains a null value:

content.code_html:
function removeErrors(obj) {
  return obj.x != null && obj.y != null;
}

content.text: Fetching Data
When you have your map and filter functions ready, you can write a function to fetch the data.
content.html: When you have your map and filter functions ready, you can write a function to fetch the data.

content.code_html:
async function runTF() {
  const jsonData = await fetch("cardata.json");
  let values = await jsonData.json();
  values = values.map(extractData).filter(removeErrors);
}

content.text: Plotting the Data
Here is some code you can use to plot the data:
content.html: Here is some code you can use to plot the data:

content.code_html:
function tfPlot(values, surface) {
  tfvis.render.scatterplot(surface,
    {values:values, series:['Original','Predicted']},
    {xLabel:'Rooms', yLabel:'Price',});
}
